    <h4>Description:</h4>
    <p>Rasmalai is a rich and creamy Indian dessert made with soft paneer balls soaked in sweetened, thickened milk flavored with cardamom and saffron. It's chilled and served as a festive treat.</p>

    <h4>Prep Time:</h4>
    <p>‚è±Ô∏è <strong>1 hour</strong></p>

    <h4>Ingredients:</h4>
    <ul>
        <li>1 liter full-fat milk (for chenna)</li>
        <li>2 tbsp lemon juice (mixed with 2 tbsp water)</li>
        <li>1/2 cup sugar</li>
        <li>2 cups water (for syrup)</li>
        <li>1 liter full-fat milk (for rabri)</li>
        <li>1/4 cup sugar (for rabri)</li>
        <li>1/4 tsp cardamom powder</li>
        <li>Few saffron strands (optional)</li>
        <li>Chopped pistachios or almonds for garnish</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>Instructions:</h4>
    <ol>
        <li>Boil 1 liter milk and add lemon-water mixture. Stir until it curdles. Drain using a muslin cloth to get chenna.</li>
        <li>Knead the chenna for 8‚Äì10 mins until smooth. Make small flat balls from it.</li>
        <li>Boil 2 cups water and 1/2 cup sugar in a pan. Add chenna balls and cook covered for 12‚Äì15 mins. They will puff up. Let them cool.</li>
        <li>In another pan, boil 1 liter milk and reduce to half. Add saffron, cardamom, and 1/4 cup sugar. Mix well to make rabri.</li>
        <li>Squeeze water from cooked rasmalai and add into rabri. Simmer for 2‚Äì3 minutes.</li>
        <li>Chill for a few hours. Garnish with nuts and serve cold.</li>
    </ol>
